  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering through several key mechanisms:\n\n1. International Treaties and Conventions\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Provide standardized frameworks for combating money laundering\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries cooperate in investigating and prosecuting money laundering\n- Sharing of financial intelligence\n- Extradition agreements\n- Cross-border legal support\n\n3. Regulatory Harmonization\n- Standardizing reporting requirements\n- Establishing common definitions of money laundering\n- Creating consistent compliance standards\n- Encouraging similar legal approaches across jurisdictions\n\n4. Financial Institution Requirements\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- Customer due diligence protocols\n- International banking compliance standards\n\n5. Enforcement Mechanisms\n- Coordinated investigations\n- Information sharing between financial intelligence units\n- Sanctions for non-compliant jurisdictions\n- International prosecution strategies\n\n6. Global Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Architecture\n- Intergovernmental organizations\n- Multilateral agreements\n- Collaborative enforcement efforts\n\nThese intersections create a complex, interconnected system addressing transnational financial crimes.",
